==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Sew
<hw>Sew</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.</pos>
<conjf>Sewed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Sewed</conjf>, rarely <conjf>Sewn</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>; <pos>p.
pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Sewing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>sewen</ets>, <ets>sowen</ets>, AS. <ets>si⟦oacute⟧wian</ets>,
<ets>s⟦imac⟧wian</ets>; akin to OHG. <ets>siuwan</ets>, Icel.
<ets>s<?/ja</ets>, Sw. <ets>sy</ets>, Dan. <ets>sye</ets>, Goth.
<ets>siujan</ets>, Lith. <ets>siuti</ets>, Russ, <ets>shite</ets>, L.
<ets>ssuere</ets>, Gr. <?/<?/<?/<?/, Skr. <ets>siv</ets>. ⟦root⟧156. Cf.
<er>Seam</er> a suture, <er>Suture</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
unite or fasten together by stitches, as with a needle and
thread.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No man also <qex>seweth</qex> a piece of new cloth on an old
garment.</q> <rj><qau>Mark ii. 21.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To close or stop by ssewing; -- often with
<xex>up</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>sew</ex> up a rip</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To inclose by sewing; -- sometimes with
<xex>up</xex>; <as>as, to <ex>sew</ex> money in a bag</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sew</ent>⟦br⟧

